---
import MainLayout from "../layouts/MainLayout.astro";
---

<MainLayout
  title="AI vs Fiverr vs Agency | Logo Brief Guide"
  description="Compare AI logo tools, Fiverr designers, and agencies so you can choose the right path for your budget, speed, and brand stakes."
  pathname="/ai-vs-fiverr-vs-agency/"
>
  <section class="prose">
    <p class="eyebrow">Decision page</p>
    <h1>AI vs Fiverr vs agency</h1>
    <p>
      All three can be right. The question is not which option is universally
      best. The question is which one matches your budget, speed, and how much
      the logo really matters to the business.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="soft-card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Option</th>
            <th>Good fit when</th>
            <th>Watch out for</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>AI</td>
            <td>Starter project, low budget, very fast turnaround.</td>
            <td>Generic results, weak refinement, unclear ownership expectations.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Fiverr</td>
            <td>Need a human designer, want revisions, budget matters.</td>
            <td>Quality varies widely, bad briefs lead to bad results.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Agency</td>
            <td>Serious business, broader brand system, higher stakes.</td>
            <td>Higher cost and slower process.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section card-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Choose AI if</p>
      <h2>You mostly need speed</h2>
      <p>
        AI can be enough for side projects, throwaway tests, or very early-stage
        brands that just need something passable now.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Choose Fiverr if</p>
      <h2>You want the best balance</h2>
      <p>
        Fiverr is often the most practical middle path when you want a real human
        but do not want agency pricing.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Choose an agency if</p>
      <h2>The brand stakes are high</h2>
      <p>
        If the logo will live on trucks, packaging, signage, or a serious long-term
        brand, deeper strategy and refinement may be worth the cost.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Best next move</h2>
      <p>
        Before you choose, tighten your brief. Good buyers usually get better
        results at every budget level because they know what they are asking for.
      </p>
      <p><a class="button" href="/logo-brief-template/">Use the brief template first</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</MainLayout>
